    "creation_date" : 1296230475,
    "answer_id" : 4830301,
    "question_id" : 4830253,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>keytool</code> is a tool to manage (public/private) security keys and certificates and store them in a <code>Java KeyStore</code> file (stored_file_name.jks).<br />\nIt is provided with any standard <code>JDK</code>/<code>JRE</code> distributions.<br />\nYou can find it under the following folder <code>%JAVA_HOME%\\bin</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 239884,
      "reputation" : 380,
      "user_id" : 509769,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e0235deee3292c1270132554ef0d15ba?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Adam Davis",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/509769/adam-davis"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 12,
    "last_activity_date" : 1373604468,
    "creation_date" : 1373604468,
    "answer_id" : 17607614,
    "question_id" : 4830253,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>For me it turned out to be in c/Program Files/Java/jdk1.7.0_25/bin (Windows 8). A more general answer to this question is that it will most likely be in the bin sub directory of wherever your jdk is installed. </p>\n"
